<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-332-783  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 332 783.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Feb 6 1989 v15 n3 p86(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>This is one Force that VME vendors must reckon with. (ForceComputers Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whiting, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Force Computers Inc has grown into the second largest maker ofVMEbus boards, behind Motorola Inc. The seven-year-old company wasstarted by a former Motorola BiPolar General Manager, SvenBehrendt.andP;  The company sells only VME-based boards and is 100percent employee owned.andP;  The company is now faced with thesaturation of the VME market and a search for direction in themarket.andP;  Force reportedly has annual sales of $40 million, andexpects to reach $100 million by 1992.andP;  About 47 percent of thecompany's sales are in the US, although much of its workforce isbased in Munich, West Germany.andP;  The company sells about 70 percentof its boards in the commercial market, the remainder to militaryunits.andP;  Force has seen annual growth rate of nearly 60 percent.andO;The company is reportedly on the verge of an initial publicoffering when market conditions are right.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Force Computers Inc. (growth).andO;Topic:     VMEbusBoards-CardsMarket ShareGrowthCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>